review_blob: Loaded with character for a wheat beer. Surprisingly amber orange, with a nice thick head you can almost sculpt. Nose was faint, I thought, but nice. Lovely body, malty, with citrus notes subdued but present. Feels good in the mouth. I like this one.

This one deserves more attention, I think. Its crispy, likes to be cold, and is quite clean and refreshing. Not as citrusy as other wheat beers Ive tried, but a very solid body and a great beer for summer drinking.
Lots of caramel in this one. Pours dark, nice aroma ... but ultimately not as satisfying to me as the Traquair House Ale. Im willing to drink more, though, in the name of science.
Oh .... yeah. Dark pour, soft but brilliant aroma, silky feel in the mouth. Creamy body. Complex series of flavors. Lovely aftertaste. Gimme more.
Pours almost black. Roasty malt aroma. Very nicely balanced. Malty body. Very nice, especially for the price.
Pours lovely cloudy gold, nice long-lasting head. Aroma is mild and somewhat citrus. Nice body. It likes to be cold. Goes great with summer foods.

Wow. Very funky, indeed. Ommegang is easily my favorite American brewery, so I popped the cork on this one with high expectations. I was not disappointed. My bottles came from Batch 2, March 2008. Pours lovely cloudy gold, nice head. Aroma is citrus and yeast. Body has a lot of bite to it, feels wonderful in the mouth. A bit tart. It likes to be cold. I have more, and cant wait to pop open another.
Im not a lager guy, but this is a good one, Nice amber/gold pour, good head, nice hoppy aroma, lovely clean taste, crisp. It wants to be served cold.
beer_name: Samuel Smiths Pure Brewed Organic Lager

review_blob: Im not a lager guy, but this is a good one, Nice amber pour, good head, nice oppy aroma, lovely clean taste,
Dark, almost black. Tan head lasts a while. Serve at cellar temperature, Dark chocolate in the taste, feels great in the mouth. Some nuttiness. Aftertaste lingers a bit. Excellent beer.
Dark brown pour. Tan head is beautiful. Dark chocalate and silk in the taste, feels great in the mouth. Very smooth. Some nuttiness.

Whoa. This is the best beer Ive had from Great Lakes Brewing Company. Dark, almost black. Tan head is beautiful. Dark chocalate and silk in the taste, feels great in the mouth. Some nuttiness in the aftertaste. Aftertaste lingers a bit. A brilliantly executed porter.

I dont drink a lot of pils, but I like this one. Its intensely hoppy. Pours a lovely gold. It likes to be served cold on a hot day. Full-bodoed. slightly citrusy, a perfect session beer for being outside fishing, or playng softball, or grilling burgers, or just sitting on the porch with friends.
Pours a light orangish, with a small white head that vanishes soon. Aroma is tart and cidery. Fruity, tart and sweet at the same time. A refreshing, distinctive beer that Id reach for on a hot day.
Honestly, Im not sure why anyone thought this was a good idea. Dont take my rating too seriously; it is based on exactly one bottle, and I am unwilling to drink more even in the name of science.
Hazy red, lovely. Wonderful aroma. Tart body, with the sherries present but not ovewhelming, Brilliant aftertase. Close to Cantillons, in my opinion.
Some find it too fruity, but I have to say I love this stuff. The aroma is heavenly, and I think the raspberry flavor is balanced with the malts. Give me more of this, please.
Hazy red, lovely. Wonderful aroma. Tart body, with the sherries present but not ovewhelming, Brilliant aftertase.

Ive only had this bottled, but I live close enough to the brewery to go try some on tap and the bottled version is good enough that I plan to do that soon. Dark amber pour, nice head, lovely clean taste. Reminds me of Smithwycks, only better, in my opinion.
Im not sure I realized this was an IPA when I drank it, but I liked the amber hue, the solid head, the hoppy character and the nice clean finish. Pretty good beer.

Oh, how I love this beer. Pours dark brown, and youll want a glass that traps the aroma and concentrates it. The head lasts a while. The body is superb and malty, and there is something woody in the taste. Very malty. A bit vinous in the back end of the swallow, and a lingering aftertaste thats nicely bitter. A superb brew.

Pours dark brown, almost black. Very full-bodied, malty flavor, feels thick and chewy in the mouth. Something caramel in the taste. but thats not overhwhelming. Bitter on the aftertaste, but it doesnt linger too long. A very nice brew.

Very nutty aroma. Pours amber-brown. Head laces nicely. Feels good in the mouth, with more body than some brown ales. The taste is complicated, and muty, of course. Nice clean finish, with a lovely aftertaste that llingers a while.

I generally trend toward darker, stronger beers ... so take this rating for what its worth. This beer pours a cloudy pale gold, with a nice head. The citrus notes here are lighter than in other wheat beers Ive tried. (For instance, not as pronounced in a Shiner Hefe-Weizen). A good brew, but not up there with other Ommegang products.

Outstanding. I love the yeasty aroma, the dark brown hue, the tan head rich and thick. I love the malty body and the way it feels in the mouth. I love the way the flavors zip through nutty to fruity to malty --  exceedingly complex. I love the sweet finish, and the lingering aftertaste. Pour me another ... please?
Very nice, as are all the beers from Brasserie Rochefort. Yeasty flavor, bready. Pours a nice brown color. I cant put it up there with the Trappiste Rochefort 10, but its a damn good beer.
Amber-red in the glass. Nice head lasts a while. Bready in the taste and body, which I like. Some spiciness, too; coriander notes, maybe. Nicely balanced beer, and another fine product from Ommegang.

Pours a beautiful  cloudy amber-gold, with a nice white head that seems a bit yellowish in some lights. Dry taste, feels sort of bubbly in the mouth. Citrud notes quite prominent. Dry finish. Ill be getting more soon.

Im going from memory here, but I had a couple of glasses of this stuff in Gettysburg a couple of years ago and really enjoyed it. Very good pale ale, and as good a reason as any to get back to Pennsyvlania soon.
Very hoppy, all balanced nicely with the malts. Great head. Orangy-amber hue. Strongly flavored, and memorable.

Lovely. Hoppy aroma, hoppy flavor ... and all balanced nicely with the malts. Superior to Sierra Nevada Pale Ale, I think, because it is more assertive. A memorable ale, and one Ill be drinking more often.
Very nice, flavorful. Nice hoppy aroma. I like this one by itself, or mixed half-and-half with apple cider to make a snakebite.

I was expecting so much more from this beer, as I am a fan of Shiner Hefe-Weizen. The Hefe-Weizen is distinctive .... but the Shiner Bock is just another bock and not a great one, at that. 

While I wouldnt turn down a bottle of this at a party or cookout, and it is loads better than the average American lager, I probably wont be buying anymore of this.

One of my favorites. Dark in the glass, lovely silky smooth head. Complex series of tastes, all in balance. I plan to lay some down in my cellar, because I have a feeling this one would improve with age.
Very smooth, despite a highly carbonated nature. Fruity and wondewrful on the palate. Not up there with the Corsendonk Brown Ale, in my opinion, but a very nice beer.
Pours orange-golden, hazy. Decent head. A bit yeasty, although balanced with the malts. I prefer Chimay Rouge (red cap) and Chimay Blue to the white, but its a fine tasty beer.

Splendid beer. Pours a lovely dark brown. Nice head. Very malty aroma, with a hint of raisins. Complicated taste; it kind of goes through a series of raisin-plum, coffee, bready, coffee, spicy. Excellent beer, especially if you like dubbels.

Pours dark brown and reddish, small frothy head that doesnt last long but laces nicely. A bit bready (which I like) with hints of raisin and other fruits. Fruit notes in the aroma, too. Feels very full in the mouth, if that makes sense. Lovely beer.

Wonderful, distinctive beer. I like the fruity notes in the aroma, and in the overall taste. I think the beer is malty enough to balance out the fruitiness very nicely. Looks all amber loveliness in the tumbler. Just a splendid beer.

Id call the color mahogany/reddish. Brownish head. Nose is woody and spicy. Feels great on the tongue. Taste is complex, with hints of spiciness and fruit but well balanced with the malts. I really like this beer.
I bit thin for me, but something about the flavor makes me want to try one with a crisp green salad. Ive never had that thought before while drinking berr.
UPDATED: JUL 22, 2008
Lovely in the glass, with a deep amber hue and a nice foamy head. Taste starts sweet but finishes slightly bitter. More body than most lagers. Goes great with summer foods off the grill.
OK, not outstanding. Refreshing, and a step or two above many lagers. Would be nice with a toasted sub or a burger off the grill.

Frothy head is huge, beer pours very dark. Chocolate shows up in the nose along with roasty malts. Creamy, satiny mouthfeel. Complex series of flavor, with the chocolate notes kicking in at the back end of the swallow. An outstanding stout.
UPDATED: MAY 19, 2008
Not much head, but I love the citrus aroma and accents. I usually drink dark ales, but found this to be a very refreshing change of pace. Much sharper flavored than other hefeweizens Ive tried.
